"title": "5188: tearing of clothes",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5188",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Primarily associated with mourning, such action was an expression of deep sorrow and heartfelt grief. It was also a natural reaction at times of great distress and in cases of sincere repentance.</p>\n<h2>The tearing of clothes was a sign of mourning</h2>\n<h3>It was a demonstration of grief</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam1:11-2Sam1:12\">2SA 1:11–1:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam13:30-2Sam13:31\">2SA 13:30–13:31</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs2:11-2Kgs2:12\">2KI 2:11–2:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job1:20\">JOB 1:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job2:12\">JOB 2:12</a></p>\n<h3>It was often associated with wearing sackcloth</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen37:34\">GEN 37:34</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam3:31-2Sam3:32\">2SA 3:31–3:32</a></p>\n<h3>The high priest was forbidden to tear his clothes in mourning</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev21:10-Lev21:12\">LEV 21:10–21:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev10:1-Lev10:7\">LEV 10:1–10:7</a></p>\n<h2>The tearing of clothes indicated deep distress</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg11:34-Judg11:35\">JDG 11:34–11:35</a></strong> <em>Jephthah had vowed to sacrifice whatever came out of the door of his house to meet him.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen37:29\">GEN 37:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen44:12-Gen44:13\">GEN 44:12–44:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num14:1-Num14:9\">NUM 14:1–14:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh7:3-Josh7:6\">JOS 7:3–7:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs6:26-2Kgs6:30\">2KI 6:26–6:30</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs18:28-2Kgs19:4\">2KI 18:28–19:4</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa36:13-Isa37:4\">ISA 36:13–37:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth3:13-Esth4:1\">EST 3:13–4:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts14:8-Acts14:18\">ACT 14:8–14:18</a></p>\n<h2>Repentance was sometimes accompanied by the tearing of clothes</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs21:20-1Kgs21:27\">1KI 21:20–21:27</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer36:21-Jer36:24\">JER 36:21–36:24</a> <em>an indication of the lack of repentance</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Joel2:12-Joel2:14\">JOL 2:12–2:14</a> <em>God requires that the tearing of clothes should express genuine repentance.</em></p>\n<h2>Other references to the tearing of clothes</h2>\n<h3>As an expression of anger</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:63-Matt26:65\">MAT 26:63–26:65</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:61-Mark14:63\">MRK 14:61–14:63</a></p>\n<h3>To stop the spread of mildew</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev13:53-Lev13:58\">LEV 13:53–13:58</a></p>\n<h3>As a symbol of the dividing of the kingdom</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam15:27-1Sam15:28\">1SA 15:27–15:28</a></p>",
